  "prompt": "How do stingrays blow bubbles?",
  "response": "Stingrays blow bubbles primarily through their gill slits, which are located on the underside of their bodies. Unlike fish that typically release air through their mouths or gills, stingrays can expel air from these slits, creating bubbles. This can occur when they are disturbed or after they have ingested air from the water surface. Additionally, some stingrays might exhibit this behavior during feeding or interacting with their environment, though the exact reasons for bubble-blowing can vary and are not fully understood. It's a fascinating aspect of their behavior that adds to their unique adaptations in the aquatic world.",
